    "instructions": [
        {
            "msg": "Authentication is username + password over the ClickHouse native TCP protocol (port 9000 / 9440) or HTTP protocol (port 8123 / 8443). Minimal payload: {\"jsonData\":{\"host\":\"<host>\",\"port\":9000,\"protocol\":\"native\",\"secure\":false,\"username\":\"default\"},\"secureJsonData\":{\"password\":\"<password>\"}}. host and port are required — the backend hard-fails with 'invalid host' / 'invalid port' otherwise. protocol defaults to 'native' when unset; secure defaults to false. Grant the ClickHouse user only the SELECT privileges Grafana should query — the backend does not sandbox SQL, so any statement will run.",
            "tags": [
                "llm",
                "auth"
            ]
        },
        {
            "msg": "Port picker: when jsonData.secure is false use 9000 for native and 8123 for http; when secure is true use 9440 for native and 8443 for http. These are only the editor placeholders — jsonData.port must always be supplied explicitly. jsonData.path is an optional URL prefix for HTTP requests (ignored for native protocol).",
            "tags": [
                "llm",
                "connection"
            ]
        },
        {
            "msg": "TLS: set jsonData.tlsAuth=true to use a client certificate (supply secureJsonData.tlsClientCert AND secureJsonData.tlsClientKey together); set jsonData.tlsAuthWithCACert=true to verify the server's TLS cert against a custom CA (supply secureJsonData.tlsCACert); set jsonData.tlsSkipVerify=true to disable certificate verification (development only). tlsAuth and tlsAuthWithCACert are independent switches — enable either, both, or neither. TLS toggles are independent of jsonData.secure: 'secure' picks the default port and enables the driver's TLS handshake, the tlsAuth* toggles configure certificate policy on top of that handshake.",
            "tags": [
                "llm",
                "auth",
                "tls"
            ]
        },
        {
            "msg": "secureJsonData values (password, tlsCACert, tlsClientCert, tlsClientKey, and per-header secureHttpHeaders.<Name>) are write-only: they can be set or reset but never read back. Custom HTTP headers stored as secure are written under keys of the form 'secureHttpHeaders.<Header Name>' in secureJsonData while the header's plaintext name/secure flag still lives in jsonData.httpHeaders — the schema exposes the value field in that array as an empty string when secure=true. To check whether a secret is already configured on an existing datasource, read the secureJsonFields object (e.g. secureJsonFields.password == true, secureJsonFields['secureHttpHeaders.X-API-Key'] == true) instead of secureJsonData.",
            "tags": [
                "llm",
                "auth",
                "secure"
            ]
        },
        {
            "msg": "Legacy v3 storage keys the backend still accepts (pkg/plugin/settings.go:87-88,160-168): jsonData.server (renamed to jsonData.host) and jsonData.timeout (renamed to jsonData.dialTimeout). The config editor's useConfigDefaults hook migrates them into jsonData on first render; the backend also mirrors them into settings.Host / settings.DialTimeout at load time. New configurations should write host and dialTimeout directly. Timeout-like knobs (dialTimeout, queryTimeout, connMaxLifetime, maxIdleConns, maxOpenConns) are stored as JSON strings — the backend also tolerates JSON numbers as a legacy shape.",
            "tags": [
                "llm",
                "legacy"
            ]
        },
        {
            "msg": "OpenTelemetry integration: for each of the logs and traces schemas, set jsonData.logs.otelEnabled=true or jsonData.traces.otelEnabled=true and pick a version in jsonData.logs.otelVersion / jsonData.traces.otelVersion (\"latest\" or \"1.29.0\" today; see src/otel.ts) — every column-name field in that schema is then derived from the OTel column map at runtime and the editor disables the manual inputs. Default tables are otel_logs and otel_traces respectively; leave jsonData.traces.traceTimestampTableSuffix blank to inherit the OTel convention (_trace_id_ts). jsonData.configMode='single-table' plus jsonData.signalType='logs'|'traces' pins the datasource to one table and hides all other databases from the query builder.",
            "tags": [
                "llm",
                "otel",
                "settings"
            ]
        }
    ]
}
